<item>
            <title>[ENTESB-1815] XSLT transformation fails when stylesheet specified classes to load by name</title>
                <link>https://issues.jboss.org/browse/ENTESB-1815</link>
                <project id="12314570" key="ENTESB">JBoss Fuse</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;An application deployed as an OSGi bundle on Fuse 6.1.0 does XSLT stylesheet transformations. The XSLT stylesheet refers by name to Java classes whose methods are intended to be called by the transformer at runtime.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;lt;xsl:stylesheet version=&quot;1.0&quot; xmlns:xsl=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform&quot; &lt;br/&gt;
  xmlns:test=&quot;http://www.something.com/com.something.xalan.reproducer.JavaFunction&quot;&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
    &amp;lt;test&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
      &amp;lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;test:callback()&quot;/&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
    &amp;lt;/test&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;/xsl:stylesheet&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This stylesheet operation fails because, at some point, Xalan attempts to do a Class.forName() on &quot;JavaFunction&quot;, and the OSGi classloading mechanism prevents this. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A workaround that is often used in similar situations is for the application to set a thread context classloader that is aware of the classes that need to be loaded by name. However, this does not work in Fuse, because the Xalan JAR has been modified so that it does not refer to thread context classloaders. So to make the application work we must additionally replace the Fuse Xalan JAR with a stock one, putting Fuse into an untested state.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>&lt;p&gt;Red Hat JBoss Fuse 6.1.0 GA&lt;/p&gt;</environment>
